# 21b9b1499d195d85e81f0e8bce08f43a64b63d589c5f15cbbd0b9c0cb07ae268</code></pre><p>Now visit <code>http://127.0.0.1:3000</code> to see the <code>hello-dock</code> application in action.</p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card kg-width-wide"><amp-img alt="" class="kg-image i-amphtml-layout-responsive i-amphtml-layout-size-defined i-amphtml-element i-amphtml-built" height="1080" i-amphtml-layout="responsive" layout="responsive" src="https://www-freecodecamp-org.cdn.ampproject.org/i/s/www.freecodecamp.org/news/content/images/2021/01/hello-dock-dev.png" srcset="https://www-freecodecamp-org.cdn.ampproject.org/i/s/www.freecodecamp.org/news/content/images/size/w600/2021/01/hello-dock-dev.png 600w, https://www-freecodecamp-org.cdn.ampproject.org/i/s/www.freecodecamp.org/news/content/images/size/w1000/2021/01/hello-dock-dev.png 1000w, https://www-freecodecamp-org.cdn.ampproject.org/i/s/www.freecodecamp.org/news/content/images/size/w1600/2021/01/hello-dock-dev.png 1600w, https://www-freecodecamp-org.cdn.ampproject.org/i/s/www.freecodecamp.org/news/content/images/2021/01/hello-dock-dev.png 1948w" width="1948" i-amphtml-auto-lightbox-visited=""><i-amphtml-sizer slot="i-amphtml-svc" style="display:block;padding-top:55.4415%;"></i-amphtml-sizer></amp-img></figure><p>Congratulations on running your first real-world application inside a container. The code you've just written is okay but there is one big issue with it and a few places where it can be improved. Let's begin with the issue first.</p><h3 id="how-to-work-with-bind-mounts-in-docker">How to Work With Bind Mounts in Docker</h3><p>If you've worked with any front-end JavaScript framework before, you should know that the development servers in these frameworks usually come with a hot reload feature. That is if you make a change in your code, the server will reload, automatically reflecting any changes you've made immediately.</p><p>But if you make any changes in your code right now, you'll see nothing happening to your application running in the browser. This is because you're making changes in the code that you have in your local file system but the application you're seeing in the browser resides inside the container file system.</p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card kg-width-wide"><amp-img alt="" class="kg-image i-amphtml-layout-responsive i-amphtml-layout-size-defined i-amphtml-element i-amphtml-built" height="148" i-amphtml-layout="responsive" layout="responsive" src="https://www-freecodecamp-org.cdn.ampproject.org/i/s/www.freecodecamp.org/news/content/images/2021/01/local-vs-container-file-system.svg" srcset="https://www-freecodecamp-org.cdn.ampproject.org/ii/w560/s/www.freecodecamp.org/news/content/images/2021/01/local-vs-container-file-system.svg 560w, https://www-freecodecamp-org.cdn.ampproject.org/ii/w820/s/www.freecodecamp.org/news/content/images/2021/01/local-vs-container-file-system.svg 820w" width="514" i-amphtml-auto-lightbox-visited=""><i-amphtml-sizer slot="i-amphtml-svc" style="display:block;padding-top:28.7938%;"></i-amphtml-sizer></amp-img></figure><p>To solve this issue, you can again make use of a <a href="https://docs.docker.com/storage/bind-mounts/" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_top">bind mount</a>. Using bind mounts, you can easily mount one of your local file system directories inside a container. Instead of making a copy of the local file system, the bind mount can reference the local file system directly from inside the container.</p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card"><amp-img alt="" class="kg-image i-amphtml-layout-responsive i-amphtml-layout-size-defined i-amphtml-element i-amphtml-built" height="178" i-amphtml-layout="responsive" layout="responsive" src="https://www-freecodecamp-org.cdn.ampproject.org/i/s/www.freecodecamp.org/news/content/images/2021/01/bind-mounts.svg" srcset="https://www-freecodecamp-org.cdn.ampproject.org/ii/w680/s/www.freecodecamp.org/news/content/images/2021/01/bind-mounts.svg 680w, https://www-freecodecamp-org.cdn.ampproject.org/ii/w820/s/www.freecodecamp.org/news/content/images/2021/01/bind-mounts.svg 820w" width="633" i-amphtml-auto-lightbox-visited=""><i-amphtml-sizer slot="i-amphtml-svc" style="display:block;padding-top:28.1201%;"></i-amphtml-sizer></amp-img></figure><p>This way, any changes you make to your local source code will reflect immediately inside the container, &nbsp;triggering the hot reload feature of the <code>vite</code> development server. Changes made to the file system inside the container will be reflected on your local file system as well.</p><p>You've already learned in the <a href="https://www-freecodecamp-org.cdn.ampproject.org/c/s/www.freecodecamp.org/news/the-docker-handbook/amp/#working-with-executable-images">Working With Executable Images</a> sub-section, bind mounts can be created using the <code>--volume</code> or <code>-v</code> option for the <code>container run</code> or <code>container start</code> commands. Just to remind you, the generic syntax is as follows:</p><pre><code>--volume &lt;local file system directory absolute path&gt;:&lt;container file system directory absolute path&gt;:&lt;read write access&gt;</code></pre><p>Stop your previously started <code>hello-dock-dev</code> container, and start a new container by executing the following command:</p><pre><code>docker container run \
    --rm \
    --publish 3000:3000 \
    --name hello-dock-dev \
    --volume $(pwd):/home/node/app \
    hello-dock:dev

