docker network inspect --format='{{range .Containers}} {{.Name}} {{end}}' bridge

#  hello-dock</code></pre><p>As you can see from the outputs of the two <code>network inspect</code> commands, the <code>hello-dock</code> container is now attached to both the <code>skynet</code> and the default <code>bridge</code> network.</p><p>The second way of attaching a container to a network is by using the <code>--network</code> option for the <code>container run</code> or <code>container create</code> commands. The generic syntax for the option is as follows:</p><pre><code>--network &lt;network identifier&gt;</code></pre><p>To run another <code>hello-dock</code> container attached to the same network, you can execute the following command:</p><pre><code>docker container run --network skynet --rm --name alpine-box -it alpine sh

